## Macedonia

808 BC–168 BC

Macedon became a vassal state of Achaemenid Persia during the rule of Darius
Hystaspes. Following the Ionian Revolt, Persian rule over the Balkans loosened,
including over Macedon. After having successfully suppressed the revolt,
Mardonius re-subjugated Thrace and conquered Macedon, making it a fully
subordinate part of Persia in 492 BC during the reign of king Alexander I
(495–450 BC). The state eventually regained its independence during the same
long reign of King Alexander I as well, following the Greco-Persian Wars. In
the Peloponnesian War Macedon was a secondary power that alternated in support
between Sparta and Athens.

