## Kingdom of France

843–1792

France originated as West Francia (Francia Occidentalis),
the western half of the Carolingian Empire, with the Treaty
of Verdun (843). A branch of the Carolingian dynasty
continued to rule until 987, when Hugh Capet was elected
king and founded the Capetian dynasty. The territory
remained known as Francia and its ruler as rex Francorum
("king of the Franks") well into the High Middle Ages. The
first king calling himself roi de France ("king of France")
was Philip II, in 1190. France continued to be ruled by
the Capetians and their cadet lines—the Valois and
Bourbon—until the monarchy was overthrown in 1792 during
the French Revolution.

